th Dakota]]\n[[Category:Mountains of South Dakota|Rushmore]]\n[[Category:Buildings and monuments honoring American Presidents in the United States]]\n[[Category:Granite sculptures in South Dakota]]\n[[Category:Rock formations of South Dakota]]\n[[Category:Symbols of South Dakota]]\n[[Category:Monuments and memorials to Abraham Lincoln in the United States]]\n[[Category:Monuments and memorials to George Washington in the United States]]\n[[Category:Abraham Lincoln in art]]\n[[Category:George Washington in art]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of George Washington]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Abraham Lincoln]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Theodore Roosevelt]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Thomas Jefferson]]\n[[Category:Great Sioux War of 1876]]\n[[Category:1941 sculptures]]\n[[Category:Mountain monuments and memorials]]\n[[Category:Monuments and memorials on the National Register of Historic Places in South Dakota]]\n[[Category:Sculptures in South Dakota]]\n[[Category:Sculptures by Gutzon Borglum]]\n[[Category:Sculptures of Presidents of the United States]]\n[[Category:Colossal statues in the United States]]\n[[Category:Monuments and memorials to Thomas Jefferson]]\n", "name_user": "2601:81:4380:4140:7dfe:662c:9e03:c196", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(The person who created Mount Rushmore)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mount_Rushmore"}
{"title_page": "Nancy Ames (scientist)", "text_new": "{{short description|Canadian scientist}}\n{{notability|1=Biographies|date=March 2020}}\n\n'''Nancy Ames''' is a Canadian scientist with [[Agriculture and Agri-Food Canada]]<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://profils-profiles.science.gc.ca/en/profile/dr-nancy-ames|title=Dr. Nancy Ames|date=2019-05-23|website=profils-profiles.science.gc.ca|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref> known for her research on the nutrition and quality of [[Cereal|cereals]] and [[Legume|pulses]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cropsphere.com/cropsphere-2017/nancy-ames|title=Nancy Ames, Ph.D.|website=CropSphere {{!}} Sessions on market outlook, research, agronomy.|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref> She works closely with plant scientists to maximize the health benefits of new varieties and ensure that these benefits are maintained when the crops are harvested and processed. Ames also works with food processors to develop new food processing techniques and new ways to evaluate them. She has invented new food products and holds two patents. She was the scientific lead that lead to the health claim \u201c[https://www.canada.ca/en/health-canada/services/food-nutrition/food-labelling/health-claims/assessments/assessment-health-claim-about-barley-products-blood-cholesterol-lowering.html Barley beta-glucan soluble fibre and reduction of blood cholesterol, a risk factor for cardiovascular disease]\u201d which was approved by [[Health Canada]] in 2012.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.agr.gc.ca/eng/news-from-agriculture-and-agri-food-canada/scientific-achievements-in-agriculture/barley-is-in-when-it-comes-to-heart-health/?id=1378999685709|title=Barley is 'in' when it comes to heart health|last=Canada|first=Agriculture and Agri-Food Canada;Government of|date=2013-10-18|website=www.agr.gc.ca|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gobarley.com/health-nutrition/|title=Health & Nutrition {{!}} GoBarley|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref>\n\n== Biography == \n\nNancy Ames received her B.Sc. (Food Science, 1980) and M.Sc. (Plant Science, 1982) from the [[University of Manitoba]]. Ames worked as a forage crop specialist for [[Manitoba Agriculture, Food and Rural Initiatives|Manitoba Agriculture]] (1981-1984) before returning to school to pursue further graduate studies. She joined Agriculture and Agri-Food Canada's (AAFC's) Plant Research Centre in Ottawa, Ontario as a Ph.D. student in 1984, and received her Ph.D. (Crop Science, 1989) from the [[University of Guelph]], Ontario. She then began her career as a research scientist in 1989 at the Plant Research Centre in Ottawa, where she worked for five years before joining the former Cereal Research Centre in Winnipeg, Manitoba as a research scientist in 1995. In 2005, Ames's office was co-located at the [http://umanitoba.ca/centres/rcffn/index.html Richardson Centre for Functional Food and Nutraceuticals] where she continues to work for AAFC. Ames is also an adjunct professor with the University of Manitoba in the Department of Human Nutritional Sciences as well as the Department of Food Science.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Career ==\nAmes works with crop breeders, researchers and industry to develop and test new varieties and food processing techniques that maximize the health properties and potential use of Canadian grains and pulses.<ref name=\":0\" />  She has served on [http://pgdc.ca/ Western Canada's Prairie Grain Development Commitees] for Oat Quality and Wheat, Rye and Titicale Qualtiy and has contributed to the development of several new oat, wheat and barley varieties.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.realagriculture.com/2015/01/wheat-school-nutrition-considered-bringing-forward-new-wheat-varieties/|title=Wheat School: Should Nutrition be Considered When Bringing Forward New Wheat Varieties?|last=January 18|last2=says|first2=2015 at 6:57 am Ernie|website=RealAgriculture.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> Her research has shown that modern wheat varieties have a similar nutritional composition to wheat grown in Canada 150 years ago.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.realagriculture.com/2015/01/wheat-school-still-good-research-counters-popular-claims-wheats-nutritional-value/|title=Wheat School: Still Good For You \u2014 Research Counters Popular Claims About Wheat\u2019s Nutritional Value|website=RealAgriculture.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.agr.gc.ca/eng/news-from-agriculture-and-agri-food-canada/scientific-achievements-in-agriculture/wheats-nutritional-value/?id=1524749246997|title=Wheat\u2019s Nutritional Value|last=Canada|first=Agriculture and Agri-Food Canada;Government of|date=2018-04-26|website=www.agr.gc.ca|access-date=2020-04-28}}</ref>\n\nAmes research focuses on the bioactive components in cereal grains (barley, oat, wheat, and others) and pulses and their impact on human health.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://profils-profiles.science.gc.ca/en/profile/dr-nancy-ames|title=Dr. Nancy Ames|date=2019-05-23|website=profils-profiles.science.gc.ca|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://grainswest.com/2019/09/snack-machine/|title=SNACK MACHINE \u2013 grainswest|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.abic.ca/abic2017/speaker/details/nancy_ames.html|title=Speakers|website=www.abic.ca|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Manitoba|first=University of|url=https://www.winnipegfreepress.com/food-for-thought/innovation-490487751.html|title=Aug 2018: Innovation|date=2018-08-09|work=Winnipeg Free Press|access-date=2020-04-08|language=en-CA}}</ref><ref name=\":3\" /> Ames\u2019 continuous efforts towards food barley improvement were culminated in her initiative to pursue a therapeutic health claim for barley based on its cholesterol lowering properties. Ames contributed to information supporting a barley health claim in the United States, which was approved in 2006.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.topcropmanager.com/another-step-forward-for-food-barley-12890/|title=Another step forward for food barley|date=2013-02-28|website=Top Crop Manager|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref> In 2007, she initiated a similar approach in Canada. She invited a large group of barley stakeholders, including breeders, growers, processors, food scientists, nutritionists and others, to discuss the idea of a similar Canadian barley health claim. With their support, Ames and members of her laboratory took a leadership role in the detailed process of preparing a health claim petition, which was submitted by the [https://www.albertabarley.com/ Alberta Barley Commission], as a representative of the barley industry, to Health Canada in February 2009. In July 2012, Health Canada approved the health claim that barley fibre reduces cholesterol and risk of heart disease.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.manitobacooperator.ca/news-opinion/news/health-canada-gives-barley-permission-to-boast-about-its-health-benefits/|title=Health Canada gives barley permission to boast about its health benefits|date=2012-08-10|website=Manitoba Co-operator|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.albertabarley.com/barley-fibre-helps-lower-cholesterol-and-risk-of-heart-disease/|title=Barley fibre helps lower cholesterol and risk of heart disease {{!}} Alberta Barley|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> During this process, she also identified and completed supplementary research to support this claim.\n\nAmes has contributed significantly in the area of food product development. Her early research resulted in two food product patents: [https://patents.justia.com/patent/20050025867 Processed barley food products] (Publication number: 20050025867, filed July 2004) and [https://patents.justia.com/patent/20020018835 Production of tortillas made from waxy barley cultivars] (Publication number: 20020018835, filed May 2001)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://patents.justia.com/inventor/nancy-ames|title=Nancy Ames Inventions, Patents and Patent Applications - Justia Patents Search|website=patents.justia.com|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref><ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.susanhughes.ca/canada-invents|title=Canada Invents|website=Susan Hughes|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.manitobacooperator.ca/country-crossroads/barley-flour-makes-fantastic-tortillas/|title=Barley Flour Makes Fantastic Tortillas|date=2009-12-03|website=Manitoba Co-operator|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.grainews.ca/farm-life/company-is-local-whole-grain-and-friendly/|title=Company Is \u201cLocal, Whole Grain And Friendly\u201d|date=2011-02-28|website=Grainews|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.producer.com/2003/03/public-lunch-promotes-instant-barley/|title=Public lunch promotes instant barley|date=2003-03-27|website=The Western Producer|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> She also developed \u201cinstant barley,\u201d a popcorn-like product that is \u201cready in five minutes,\u201d and contributed recipes and ideas to several cookbooks<ref name=\":6\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://fooddaycanada.ca/articles/a-new-superfood/|title=Food Day Canada presents Barley - A New Super Food|website=fooddaycanada.ca|access-date=2020-04-28}}</ref> and hosted various public events to increase the use of barley in main courses, salads and desserts<ref name=\":5\" />. Ames has developed and tested methods to use high-pea flour to create low-glycemic and nutritious baked goods such as bagels and steamed buns.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.producer.com/2016/12/building-a-better-bagel/|title=VIDEO: Building a better bagel|date=2016-12-29|website=The Western Producer|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>\n\nAmes has worked with various organizations to actively promote grains as part of a healthy diet.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.gobarley.com/cookbook/|title=GoBarley Cookbook: Modern Recipes for an Ancient Grain {{!}} GoBarley|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.amazon.ca/Homegrown-Celebrating-Canadian-Foods-Produce/dp/1770502327|website=www.amazon.ca|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://fooddaycanada.ca/articles/a-new-superfood/|title=Food Day Canada presents Barley - A New Super Food|website=fooddaycanada.ca|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=Built On Agriculture {{!}} Part 4: Feeding the World|url=https://www.pbs.org/video/part-4-feeding-the-world-cs3lql/|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> She has been invited as a guest speaker at many scientiific<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://canolaeatwell.com/dr-ames-presents-does-science-belong-on-my-plate/|title=Dr. Ames presents: Does Science Belong On My Plate?|last=Sandi|date=2014-11-12|website=Eat Well|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> and public events as a scientific authority on the health properties of grains and pulses.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.producer.com/2013/12/oat-sector-needs-to-get-doctors-to-tout-benefits/|title=Oat sector needs to get doctors to tout benefits|date=2013-12-19|website=The Western Producer|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://canadianfoodbusiness.com/2013/11/07/ideal-grain-ingredients-breeding-wheat-for-health/|title=Ideal Grain Ingredients: BREEDING WHEAT FOR HEALTH|last=Nicole|date=2013-11-07|website=Canadian Food Business|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://issuu.com/woodruffsweitzer/docs/estc-219_ng_spring2013_can_hr|title=Newground Magazine Spring 2013 Canada|website=Issuu|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> As part of this promotion, she also helped organize the \u201cWorld\u2019s Biggest Bowl of Oatmeal<ref name=\":7\" />,\u201d and has appeared on various Canadian TV Shows. She has been an active member of the American Association of Cereal Chemists International and has served on the scientific advisory boards for the [http://healthygrains.ca Healthy Grains Institute] and the [https://www.quakeroats.com/about-quaker-oats/quaker-oats-center-of-excellence Quaker Oats Center of Excellence].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> \n\nShe also studies how processing affects the functionality and health benefits of grain and pulse based foods.<ref name=\":0\" /> To accomplish this, she has also helped develop analytical and ''in vitro'' methods to predict health benefits<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":4\" /> and leads collaborative studies including clinical trials. For example, her research recently discovered that barley is beneficial for the [[Human gastrointestinal microbiota|gut\u00a0microbiome]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.agr.gc.ca/eng/news-from-agriculture-and-agri-food-canada/scientific-achievements-in-agriculture/barley-a-top-crop-from-your-heart-to-your-gut/?id=1474570674846|title=Barley: A top crop from your heart to your gut|last=Canada|first=Agriculture and Agri-Food Canada;Government of|date=2016-09-26|website=www.agr.gc.ca|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wang|first=Yanan|last2=Ames|first2=Nancy P.|last3=Tun|first3=Hein M.|last4=Tosh|first4=Susan M.|last5=Jones|first5=Peter J.|last6=Khafipour|first6=Ehsan|date=2016-02-10|title=High Molecular Weight Barley \u03b2-Glucan Alters Gut Microbiota Toward Reduced Cardiovascular Disease Risk|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4748052/|journal=Frontiers in Microbiology|volume=7|doi=10.3389/fmicb.2016.00129|issn=1664-302X|pmc=4748052|pmid=26904005}}</ref> Barley [[beta-glucan]] can act as a prebiotic by modulating the composition of the microbiota in the gut, which can improve overall metabolic health in humans. This barley cholesterol clinical trial was also the first to show that human genetic background impacts physiological response to barley consumption, contributing novel findings to the field of nutrigenomics. These ground breaking discoveries along with her continued exploration of health benefits of cereal grains and pulses such as improved glycemic response will advance the level of academia's knowledge of Canadian grain and pulse nutrition.\n\nAmes is actively involved in the [http://www.vernajkirkness.org/ Verna J. Kirkness Science and Engineering Education Program] which brings Indigenous Grade 11 students from Winnipeg, rural and northern Manitoba, British Columbia, and New Brunswick to the University of Manitoba campus to experience first-hand the joy of scientific research. Students representing [[First Nations]], [[M\u00e9tis]] and [[Inuit]] communities come to campus to be mentored by more than 100 professors, [[Postdoctoral Fellows|postdoctoral fellows]], graduate and undergraduate students, and research technicians.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.umanitoba.ca/future-indigenous-scientists-from-across-canada-come-to-campus|title=Future Indigenous scientists from across Canada come to campus|last=Manitoba - //www.umanitoba.ca|first=University of|language=en|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref>\n\nAmes has authored and co-authored over 85 peer-reviewed publications, numerous abstracts and several book chapters. <ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Honours and awards  ==\n\n* 2018 \u00a0 \u00a0Recipient of Agriculture and Agri-Food Canada's Prize for Outstanding Achievement in Science\n\n* 2016 \u00a0 \u00a0Mentor of the year award in recognition of outstanding contributions to the Sanofi-Aventis BioTalent Challenge. \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \n* 2015 \u00a0 \u00a0American Association of Cereal Chemists International [http://www.aaccnet.org/membership/awards/Pages/EdithAChristensen.aspx Edith Christensen Award].\n* 2012 \u00a0\u00a0 Accuracy Award for Analysis of Dietary Fiber, for the most accurate and precise results in 2011 for insoluble, soluble, total dietary fiber and beta-glucan.\n* 2012 \u00a0 \u00a0Recognition of Analytical Performance in Analysis of Dietary Fiber, with an \"Outstanding Accuracy and Precision\" rating for 2011 for insoluble, soluble, total dietary fiber and beta-glucan.\n* Led a team of volunteers who on March 20, 2010 prepared a 327.5 kg bowl of oatmeal \u2013 setting a new world record for the '''Largest Bowl of Oatmeal''' (close to double the previous Guinness world record of 171.9 kilograms).<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.worldrecordacademy.com/food/largest_bowl_of_oatmeal_world_record_set_by_Agriculture_and_Agri-Food_Canada_101611.htm|title=Largest Bowl of Oatmeal - world record set by Agriculture and Agri-Food Canada|website=www.worldrecordacademy.com|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref>\n* 2010 \u00a0 \u00a0AAFC Instant Award for achieving the Guinness world record for the biggest bowl of oatmeal, and the success of the 2010 CIFST-AAFC Conference and AAFC Food Network Meeting.\n* 2008 \u00a0 \u00a0[[American Association of Cereal Chemists]] International Accuracy Award for Dietary Fiber Analysis.\n* 2008 \u00a0\u00a0 American Association of Cereal Chemists International Certificate of Proficiency for Dietary Fiber Analysis.\n* 2007-2008 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0Biotech Challenge Mentor of the Year-Distinction, Aventis Biotech Challenge CANADA<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ames, Nancy}}\n[[Category:Canadian scientists]]\n[[Category:Canadian women scientists]]\n[[Category:University of Manitoba alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Guelph alumni]]\n[[Category:Agriculture and Agri-Food Canada]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Canadian scientist}}\n{{notability|1=Biographies|date=March 2020}}\n\n'''Nancy Ames''' is a Canadian scientist with [[Agriculture and Agri-Food Canada]]<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://profils-profiles.science.gc.ca/en/profile/dr-nancy-ames|title=Dr. Nancy Ames|date=2019-05-23|website=profils-profiles.science.gc.ca|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref> known for her research on the nutrition and quality of [[Cereal|cereals]] and [[Legume|pulses]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cropsphere.com/cropsphere-2017/nancy-ames|title=Nancy Ames, Ph.D.|website=CropSphere {{!}} Sessions on market outlook, research, agronomy.|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref> She works closely with plant scientists to maximize the health benefits of new varieties and ensure that these benefits are maintained when the crops are harvested and processed. Ames also works with food processors to develop new food processing techniques and new ways to evaluate them. She has invented new food products and holds two patents. She was the scientific lead that lead to the health claim \u201c[https://www.canada.ca/en/health-canada/services/food-nutrition/food-labelling/health-claims/assessments/assessment-health-claim-about-barley-products-blood-cholesterol-lowering.html Barley beta-glucan soluble fibre and reduction of blood cholesterol, a risk factor for cardiovascular disease]\u201d which was approved by [[Health Canada]] in 2012.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.agr.gc.ca/eng/news-from-agriculture-and-agri-food-canada/scientific-achievements-in-agriculture/barley-is-in-when-it-comes-to-heart-health/?id=1378999685709|title=Barley is 'in' when it comes to heart health|last=Canada|first=Agriculture and Agri-Food Canada;Government of|date=2013-10-18|website=www.agr.gc.ca|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gobarley.com/health-nutrition/|title=Health & Nutrition {{!}} GoBarley|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref>\n\n== Biography == \n\nNancy Ames received her B.Sc. (Food Science, 1980) and M.Sc. (Plant Science, 1982) from the [[University of Manitoba]]. Ames worked as a forage crop specialist for [[Manitoba Agriculture, Food and Rural Initiatives|Manitoba Agriculture]] (1981-1984) before returning to school to pursue further graduate studies. She joined Agriculture and Agri-Food Canada's (AAFC's) Plant Research Centre in Ottawa, Ontario as a Ph.D. student in 1984, and received her Ph.D. (Crop Science, 1989) from the [[University of Guelph]], Ontario. She then began her career as a research scientist in 1989 at the Plant Research Centre in Ottawa, where she worked for five years before joining the former Cereal Research Centre in Winnipeg, Manitoba as a research scientist in 1995. In 2005, Ames's office was co-located at the [http://umanitoba.ca/centres/rcffn/index.html Richardson Centre for Functional Food and Nutraceuticals] where she continues to work for AAFC. Ames is also an adjunct professor with the University of Manitoba in the Department of Human Nutritional Sciences as well as the Department of Food Science.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Career ==\nAmes works with crop breeders, researchers and industry to develop and test new varieties and food processing techniques that maximize the health properties and potential use of Canadian grains and pulses.<ref name=\":0\" />  She has served on [http://pgdc.ca/ Western Canada's Prairie Grain Development Commitees] for Oat Quality and Wheat, Rye and Titicale Qualtiy and has contributed to the development of several new oat, wheat and barley varieties.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.realagriculture.com/2015/01/wheat-school-nutrition-considered-bringing-forward-new-wheat-varieties/|title=Wheat School: Should Nutrition be Considered When Bringing Forward New Wheat Varieties?|last=January 18|last2=says|first2=2015 at 6:57 am Ernie|website=RealAgriculture.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> Her research has shown that modern wheat varieties have a similar nutritional composition to wheat grown in Canada 150 years ago.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.realagriculture.com/2015/01/wheat-school-still-good-research-counters-popular-claims-wheats-nutritional-value/|title=Wheat School: Still Good For You \u2014 Research Counters Popular Claims About Wheat\u2019s Nutritional Value|website=RealAgriculture.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.agr.gc.ca/eng/news-from-agriculture-and-agri-food-canada/scientific-achievements-in-agriculture/wheats-nutritional-value/?id=1524749246997|title=Wheat\u2019s Nutritional Value|last=Canada|first=Agriculture and Agri-Food Canada;Government of|date=2018-04-26|website=www.agr.gc.ca|access-date=2020-04-28}}</ref>\n\nAmes research focuses on the bioactive components in cereal grains (barley, oat, wheat, and others) and pulses and their impact on human health.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://profils-profiles.science.gc.ca/en/profile/dr-nancy-ames|title=Dr. Nancy Ames|date=2019-05-23|website=profils-profiles.science.gc.ca|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://grainswest.com/2019/09/snack-machine/|title=SNACK MACHINE \u2013 grainswest|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.abic.ca/abic2017/speaker/details/nancy_ames.html|title=Speakers|website=www.abic.ca|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Manitoba|first=University of|url=https://www.winnipegfreepress.com/food-for-thought/innovation-490487751.html|title=Aug 2018: Innovation|date=2018-08-09|work=Winnipeg Free Press|access-date=2020-04-08|language=en-CA}}</ref><ref name=\":3\" /> Ames\u2019 continuous efforts towards food barley improvement were culminated in her initiative to pursue a therapeutic health claim for barley based on its cholesterol lowering properties. Ames contributed to information supporting a barley health claim in the United States, which was approved in 2006.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.topcropmanager.com/another-step-forward-for-food-barley-12890/|title=Another step forward for food barley|date=2013-02-28|website=Top Crop Manager|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref> In 2007, she initiated a similar approach in Canada. She invited a large group of barley stakeholders, including breeders, growers, processors, food scientists, nutritionists and others, to discuss the idea of a similar Canadian barley health claim. With their support, Ames and members of her laboratory took a leadership role in the detailed process of preparing a health claim petition, which was submitted by the [https://www.albertabarley.com/ Alberta Barley Commission], as a representative of the barley industry, to Health Canada in February 2009. In July 2012, Health Canada approved the health claim that barley fibre reduces cholesterol and risk of heart disease.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.manitobacooperator.ca/news-opinion/news/health-canada-gives-barley-permission-to-boast-about-its-health-benefits/|title=Health Canada gives barley permission to boast about its health benefits|date=2012-08-10|website=Manitoba Co-operator|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.albertabarley.com/barley-fibre-helps-lower-cholesterol-and-risk-of-heart-disease/|title=Barley fibre helps lower cholesterol and risk of heart disease {{!}} Alberta Barley|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> During this process, she also identified and completed supplementary research to support this claim.\n\nShe also studies how processing affects the functionality and health benefits of grain and pulse based foods.<ref name=\":0\" /> To accomplish this, she has also helped develop analytical and ''in vitro'' methods to predict health benefits.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.producer.com/2016/12/building-a-better-bagel/|title=VIDEO: Building a better bagel|date=2016-12-29|website=The Western Producer|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref>   \n\nAmes has contributed significantly in the area of food product development. Her early research resulted in two food product patents: [https://patents.justia.com/patent/20050025867 Processed barley food products] (Publication number: 20050025867, filed July 2004) and [https://patents.justia.com/patent/20020018835 Production of tortillas made from waxy barley cultivars] (Publication number: 20020018835, filed May 2001)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://patents.justia.com/inventor/nancy-ames|title=Nancy Ames Inventions, Patents and Patent Applications - Justia Patents Search|website=patents.justia.com|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref><ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.susanhughes.ca/canada-invents|title=Canada Invents|website=Susan Hughes|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.manitobacooperator.ca/country-crossroads/barley-flour-makes-fantastic-tortillas/|title=Barley Flour Makes Fantastic Tortillas|date=2009-12-03|website=Manitoba Co-operator|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.grainews.ca/farm-life/company-is-local-whole-grain-and-friendly/|title=Company Is \u201cLocal, Whole Grain And Friendly\u201d|date=2011-02-28|website=Grainews|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.producer.com/2003/03/public-lunch-promotes-instant-barley/|title=Public lunch promotes instant barley|date=2003-03-27|website=The Western Producer|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> She also developed \u201cinstant barley,\u201d a popcorn-like product that is \u201cready in five minutes,\u201d and contributed recipes and ideas to several cookbooks<ref name=\":6\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://fooddaycanada.ca/articles/a-new-superfood/|title=Food Day Canada presents Barley - A New Super Food|website=fooddaycanada.ca|access-date=2020-04-28}}</ref> and hosted various public events to increase the use of barley in main courses, salads and desserts<ref name=\":5\" />. Ames has developed and tested methods to use high-pea flour to create low-glycemic and nutritious baked goods such as bagels and steamed buns.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nAmes has worked with various organizations to actively promote grains as part of a healthy diet.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.gobarley.com/cookbook/|title=GoBarley Cookbook: Modern Recipes for an Ancient Grain {{!}} GoBarley|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.amazon.ca/Homegrown-Celebrating-Canadian-Foods-Produce/dp/1770502327|website=www.amazon.ca|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://fooddaycanada.ca/articles/a-new-superfood/|title=Food Day Canada presents Barley - A New Super Food|website=fooddaycanada.ca|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=Built On Agriculture {{!}} Part 4: Feeding the World|url=https://www.pbs.org/video/part-4-feeding-the-world-cs3lql/|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> She has been invited as a guest speaker at many scientiific<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://canolaeatwell.com/dr-ames-presents-does-science-belong-on-my-plate/|title=Dr. Ames presents: Does Science Belong On My Plate?|last=Sandi|date=2014-11-12|website=Eat Well|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> and public events as a scientific authority on the health properties of grains and pulses.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.producer.com/2013/12/oat-sector-needs-to-get-doctors-to-tout-benefits/|title=Oat sector needs to get doctors to tout benefits|date=2013-12-19|website=The Western Producer|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://canadianfoodbusiness.com/2013/11/07/ideal-grain-ingredients-breeding-wheat-for-health/|title=Ideal Grain Ingredients: BREEDING WHEAT FOR HEALTH|last=Nicole|date=2013-11-07|website=Canadian Food Business|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://issuu.com/woodruffsweitzer/docs/estc-219_ng_spring2013_can_hr|title=Newground Magazine Spring 2013 Canada|website=Issuu|language=en|access-date=2020-04-08}}</ref> As part of this promotion, she also helped organize the \u201cWorld\u2019s Biggest Bowl of Oatmeal<ref name=\":7\" />,\u201d and has appeared on various Canadian TV Shows. She has been an active member of the American Association of Cereal Chemists International and has served on the scientific advisory boards for the [http://healthygrains.ca Healthy Grains Institute] and the [https://www.quakeroats.com/about-quaker-oats/quaker-oats-center-of-excellence Quaker Oats Center of Excellence].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\" /> \n\nAmes continues to explore the role barley plays in human nutrition by leading collaborative studies including clinical trials. For example, this research recently discovered that barley is beneficial for the [[Human gastrointestinal microbiota|gut\u00a0microbiome]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.agr.gc.ca/eng/news-from-agriculture-and-agri-food-canada/scientific-achievements-in-agriculture/barley-a-top-crop-from-your-heart-to-your-gut/?id=1474570674846|title=Barley: A top crop from your heart to your gut|last=Canada|first=Agriculture and Agri-Food Canada;Government of|date=2016-09-26|website=www.agr.gc.ca|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wang|first=Yanan|last2=Ames|first2=Nancy P.|last3=Tun|first3=Hein M.|last4=Tosh|first4=Susan M.|last5=Jones|first5=Peter J.|last6=Khafipour|first6=Ehsan|date=2016-02-10|title=High Molecular Weight Barley \u03b2-Glucan Alters Gut Microbiota Toward Reduced Cardiovascular Disease Risk|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4748052/|journal=Frontiers in Microbiology|volume=7|doi=10.3389/fmicb.2016.00129|issn=1664-302X|pmc=4748052|pmid=26904005}}</ref> Barley [[beta-glucan]] can act as a prebiotic by modulating the composition of the microbiota in the gut, which can improve overall metabolic health in humans. This barley cholesterol clinical trial was also the first to show that human genetic background impacts physiological response to barley consumption, contributing novel findings to the field of nutrigenomics. These ground breaking discoveries along with her continued exploration of health benefits of cereal grains and pulses such as improved glycemic response will advance the level of academia's knowledge of Canadian grain and pulse nutrition.\n\nAmes is actively involved in the [http://www.vernajkirkness.org/ Verna J. Kirkness Science and Engineering Education Program] which brings Indigenous Grade 11 students from Winnipeg, rural and northern Manitoba, British Columbia, and New Brunswick to the University of Manitoba campus to experience first-hand the joy of scientific research. Students representing [[First Nations]], [[M\u00e9tis]] and [[Inuit]] communities come to campus to be mentored by more than 100 professors, [[Postdoctoral Fellows|postdoctoral fellows]], graduate and undergraduate students, and research technicians.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.umanitoba.ca/future-indigenous-scientists-from-across-canada-come-to-campus|title=Future Indigenous scientists from across Canada come to campus|last=Manitoba - //www.umanitoba.ca|first=University of|language=en|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref>\n\nAmes has authored and co-authored over 85 peer-reviewed publications, numerous abstracts and several book chapters. <ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Honours and awards  ==\n2018 \u00a0 \u00a0Recipient of Agriculture and Agri-Food Canada's Prize for Outstanding Achievement in Science\n\n* 2016 \u00a0 \u00a0Mentor of the year award in recognition of outstanding contributions to the Sanofi-Aventis BioTalent Challenge. \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \n* 2015 \u00a0 \u00a0American Association of Cereal Chemists International [http://www.aaccnet.org/membership/awards/Pages/EdithAChristensen.aspx Edith Christensen Award].\n* 2012 \u00a0\u00a0 Accuracy Award for Analysis of Dietary Fiber, for the most accurate and precise results in 2011 for insoluble, soluble, total dietary fiber and beta-glucan.\n* 2012 \u00a0 \u00a0Recognition of Analytical Performance in Analysis of Dietary Fiber, with an \"Outstanding Accuracy and Precision\" rating for 2011 for insoluble, soluble, total dietary fiber and beta-glucan.\n* Led a team of volunteers who on March 20, 2010 prepared a 327.5 kg bowl of oatmeal \u2013 setting a new world record for the '''Largest Bowl of Oatmeal''' (close to double the previous Guinness world record of 171.9 kilograms).<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.worldrecordacademy.com/food/largest_bowl_of_oatmeal_world_record_set_by_Agriculture_and_Agri-Food_Canada_101611.htm|title=Largest Bowl of Oatmeal - world record set by Agriculture and Agri-Food Canada|website=www.worldrecordacademy.com|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref>\n* 2010 \u00a0 \u00a0AAFC Instant Award for achieving the Guinness world record for the biggest bowl of oatmeal, and the success of the 2010 CIFST-AAFC Conference and AAFC Food Network Meeting.\n* 2008 \u00a0 \u00a0[[American Association of Cereal Chemists]] International Accuracy Award for Dietary Fiber Analysis.\n* 2008 \u00a0\u00a0 American Association of Cereal Chemists International Certificate of Proficiency for Dietary Fiber Analysis.\n* 2007-2008 \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0Biotech Challenge Mentor of the Year-Distinction, Aventis Biotech Challenge CANADA<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ames, Nancy}}\n[[Category:Canadian scientists]]\n[[Category:Canadian women scientists]]\n[[Category:University of Manitoba alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Guelph alumni]]\n[[Category:Agriculture and Agri-Food Canada]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "AgriScience", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCareer", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nancy_Ames_(scientist)"}
{"title_page": "Chris Wedge", "text_new": "{{short description|American animator}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image         =  Chris Wedge 2014.jpg\n| caption       = Wedge in 2014\n| birth_name    = John Christian Wedge\n| name          = Chris Wedge\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1957|3|20|mf=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[Binghamton, New York]], U.S.\n| nationality   = American\n| education     = [[Fayetteville-Manlius High School]]\n| alma_mater    = [[State University of New York at Purchase]]<br>[[Ohio State University]]\n| occupation    = Film director, film producer, screenwriter, cartoonist, voice actor\n| yearsactive   = 1982\u2013present\n| notable_works = ''[[Ice Age (2002 film)|Ice Age]]''<br>''[[Robots (2005 film)|Robots]]''<br>''[[Epic (2013 film)|Epic]]''<br>''[[Monster Trucks (film)|Monster Trucks]]''\n| spouse        = Jeanne Markel<ref name=TNYTBunnyOscar />\n| children = 2\n}}\n\n'''John Christian Wedge''' (born March 20, 1957) is an American [[animated film]] director,  producer, writer, cartoonist and voice actor, whose films include ''[[Ice Age (2002 film)|Ice Age]]'' (2002), ''[[Robots (2005 film)|Robots]]'' (2005), ''[[Epic (2013 film)|Epic]]'' (2013) and ''[[Monster Trucks (film)|Monster Trucks]]'' (2016). He is a co-founder of the animation studio [[Blue Sky Studios]] and voiced the character [[Scrat]] in the ''[[Ice Age (franchise)|Ice Age]]'' franchise.\n\n==Early life==\nWedge was born in [[Binghamton, New York]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.behindthevoiceactors.com/Chris-Wedge/ |title= Behind The Voice Actors - Chris Wedge |accessdate=April 14, 2014}}</ref> He became interested in animation when he was 12 years old: \"Back then, there was a TV special about kids making cut-out animation in a workshop\u2014as I recall it was Yellow Ball Workshop\u2014it was a clear technique to follow and I followed it. That fascinated me and it got me started. It was so simple, effective and magical in outcome and I stuck with creating things throughout my childhood, teenage years and then college.\"<ref name=PatchKatonah>{{cite news|last=Buchman|first=Lisa|title=Meet Chris Wedge, 'Ice Age' Creator, Katonah Resident|url=http://bedford.patch.com/articles/meet-chris-wedge-ice-age-director-and-katonah-resident|accessdate=November 29, 2012|newspaper=Patch|date=September 12, 2012}}</ref>\n\nHe attended [[Fayetteville-Manlius High School]], graduating in 1975.<ref name=\"distinction\">{{cite web | title = Chris Wedge, Class of 1975, Inducted in 2000 | work = Fayetteville-Manlius Hall of Distinction | publisher = Fayetteville-Manlius Schools | url = http://www.fmschools.org/community.cfm?subpage=16023 | accessdate = May 29, 2011 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110724182939/http://www.fmschools.org/community.cfm?subpage=16023 | archive-date = July 24, 2011 | url-status = dead | df = mdy-all }}</ref> He received his BFA in Film from [[State University of New York at Purchase]] in Purchase, New York in 1981, and subsequently earned his MA in [[computer graphics]] and art education at the [[Ohio State University]]. He has taught animation at the [[School of Visual Arts]] in [[New York City]] where he met his future film directing partner, [[Carlos Saldanha]].\n\n==Career==\nIn 1982, Wedge worked for [[Mathematical Applications Group, Inc.|MAGI]]/SynthaVision, where he was a principal animator on the [[The Walt Disney Company|Disney]] film ''[[Tron]]'', credited as a scene programmer. Some of his other works include ''[[Where the Wild Things Are]]'' (1983), ''George Shrinks'', ''[[The Brave Little Toaster]]'' (1987), and ''Santa Calls''.\n\nWedge is co-founder and Vice President of Creative Development at [[Blue Sky Studios]], one of the premier computer animation studios and producer of Wedge's films. He is the owner of WedgeWorks, a film production company founded by Wedge.\n\nIn the 1990s, he and his studio worked on CGI effects for the movies ''[[Alien Resurrection]]'' and ''[[Titan A.E.]]''\n\nIn 1998, he won an [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]] for the short animated film, ''[[Bunny (1998 film)|Bunny]]''. In 2002, Wedge directed Blue Sky Studios' first computer-animated film ''[[Ice Age (2002 film)|Ice Age]]'' and served as a producer for its sequels. He also voiced [[Scrat]] in the film series, performing the character's \"squeaks and squeals.\"<ref name=\"PS\">{{cite news  | last = LaRue | first = William | title = 'Ice Age' director gives students a look into animation | work = [[The Syracuse Post-Standard]] | publisher = Syracuse.com | date = November 2, 2006 | url = http://www.syracuse.com/living/poststandard/index.ssf?/base/living-2/1162461401265550.xml&coll=1 | accessdate = January 27, 2007 }}{{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> In 2005, Wedge directed ''[[Robots (2005 film)|Robots]]'', based on a story he created with [[William Joyce (writer)|William Joyce]]. In 2013 followed ''[[Epic (2013 film)|Epic]]'', loosely based on Joyce's book, ''The Leaf Men and the Brave Good Bugs''.<ref name=\"Mania\">{{cite news|last=Schneider |first=Karl |title=Chris Wedge to direct THE LEAF MEN AND THE BRAVE GOOD BUGS |work=Movie News, Mania.com |publisher=Mania Entertainment, LLC., citing [[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=August 24, 2006 |url=http://www.mania.com/52071.html |accessdate=January 27, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927021330/http://www.mania.com/52071.html |archivedate=September 27, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, it was announced that Wedge would direct ''[[Hugo (film)|Hugo]]'' though he was subsequently replaced by [[Martin Scorsese]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Siegel |first=Tatiana |url=https://www.variety.com/article/VR1117985121 |title=Chris Wedge to direct 'Hugo Cabret' |journal=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=2008-05-05 |accessdate=2012-08-24}}</ref> In 2009, it was reported that Wedge would direct an animated feature film adaptation of [[Will Wright (game designer)|Will Wright]]'s ''[[Spore (2008 video game)#Theatrical film|Spore]]'', but since then there has been no further news about the film.<ref>{{cite magazine |first=Marc |last=Graser |url=https://www.variety.com/article/VR1118009454 |title=EA sets up 'Spore' at Fox |magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=October 1, 2009 |accessdate=October 7, 2010}}</ref>\n\nWedge directed the science fiction/action film ''[[Monster Trucks (film)|Monster Trucks]]'' (2016), with a $100 million budget, and starring [[Lucas Till]] and [[Jane Levy]].<ref name=mt>{{cite news|title=Paramount Animation Plans \u2018Monster Trucks\u2019 Live Action-Toon Franchise: In Final Talks With Blue Sky\u2019s Chris Wedge To Direct|url=https://www.deadline.com/2013/07/paramout-animation-plans-monster-trucks-live-action-toon-franchise-in-final-talks-with-chris-wedge-to-direct/|accessdate=August 2, 2013|newspaper=deadline.com|date=July 31, 2013}}</ref> [[Jonathan Aibel and Glenn Berger]] wrote the script for the film,<ref name=\"mt\" /> produced by [[Mary Parent]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Paramount Animation Planning Live Action/Animated Franchise 'Monster Trucks' With Blue Sky's Chris Wedge|url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/paramount-animation-planning-live-action-animated-franchise-monster-trucks-with-blue-skys-chris-wedge-20130801|accessdate=August 2, 2013|newspaper=indiewire.com|date=August 1, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140521032045/http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/paramount-animation-planning-live-action-animated-franchise-monster-trucks-with-blue-skys-chris-wedge-20130801|archive-date=May 21, 2014|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nWedge lives in [[Katonah, New York]]<ref name=PatchKatonah /> with his wife Jeanne Markel.<ref name=TNYTBunnyOscar>{{cite news|last=Staudter|first=Thomas|title='Bunny' From Harrison Competes for Oscar|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/03/21/nyregion/bunny-from-harrison-competes-for-oscar.html|accessdate=June 2, 2013|newspaper=The New York Times|date=March 21, 1999}}</ref> They have a daughter and a son, Sarah and Jack.<ref>{{cite web|title=Chris Wedge Acceptance Speech|url=http://aaspeechesdb.oscars.org/link/071-18/|publisher=The Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences|accessdate=June 2, 2013|quote=And so to my beautiful wife and family, Jean*, Sarah and Jack...}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Director===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:#b0c4de;\"| Year\n! style=\"background:#b0c4de;\" width=200px | Title\n! style=\"background:#b0c4de;\" width=400px | Notes\n|-\n| 1985 || ''Tuber's Two-Step'' || rowspan=\"2\" | Short film\n|-\n| 1987 || ''Balloon Guy''\n|-\n| 1998 || ''[[Bunny (1998 film)|Bunny]]'' || (Short Film) [[Academy Award for Best Animated Short Film]]<br>Also writer\n|-\n| 2002 || ''[[Ice Age (2002 film)|Ice Age]]'' ||  Academy Award nomination for [[Academy Award for Best Animated Feature|Best Animated Feature]]\n|-\n| 2005 || ''[[Robots (2005 film)|Robots]]'' ||\n|-\n| 2013 || ''[[Epic (2013 film)|Epic]]'' || \n|-\n| 2016 || ''[[Monster Trucks (film)|Monster Trucks]]'' ||\n|}\n\n===Producer===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:#b0c4de;\"| Year\n! style=\"background:#b0c4de;\" width=200px | Title\n! style=\"background:#b0c4de;\" width=400px | Notes\n|-\n| 1990 || ''The Mind's Eye'' || Short film\n|-\n| 2002 || ''[[Gone Nutty]]'' || rowspan=\"4\" | Executive producer\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2006 || ''[[Ice Age: The Meltdown]]''\n|-\n| ''[[No Time for Nuts]]''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2008 || ''[[Horton Hears a Who! (film)|Horton Hears a Who!]]'' \n|-\n| ''[[Surviving Sid]]'' || Short film<br />Executive producer\n|-\n| 2009 || ''[[Ice Age: Dawn of the Dinosaurs]]'' || rowspan=\"7\"  | Executive producer\n|-\n| 2011 || ''[[Rio (2011 film)|Rio]]'' \n|-\n| 2012 || ''[[Ice Age: Continental Drift]]''\n|-\n| 2014 || ''[[Rio 2]]''\n|-\n| 2016 || ''[[Ice Age: Collision Course]]''<ref name=USATSquirrelMacy>{{cite news|last1=Truitt|first1=Brian|title=Exclusive: 'Ice Age' squirrel to make Macy's debut|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/movies/2015/10/22/exclusive-ice-age-scrat-balloon-macys-thanksgiving-day-parade/74366580/|accessdate=October 29, 2015|work=USA Today|date=October 22, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2017 || ''[[Ferdinand (film)|Ferdinand]]''\n|-\n| 2019 || ''[[Spies in Disguise]]''\n|}\n\n===Animator===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:#b0c4de;\"| Year\n! style=\"background:#b0c4de;\" width=200px | Title\n! style=\"background:#b0c4de;\" width=400px | Notes\n|-\n| 1982 || ''[[Tron]]'' || Principal animator\n|-\n| 1987 || ''Balloon Guy'' || Animator\n|-\n| 1996 || ''[[Joe's Apartment]]'' || Animation director\n|}\n\n===Writer===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:#b0c4de;\"| Year\n! style=\"background:#b0c4de;\" width=200px | Title\n! style=\"background:#b0c4de;\" width=400px | Notes\n|-\n| 1998 || ''[[Bunny (1998 film)|Bunny]]'' ||\n|-\n| 2013 || ''[[Epic (2013 film)|Epic]]'' || Story\n|}\n\n===Actor===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:#b0c4de;\"| Year\n! style=\"background:#b0c4de;\" width=200px | Title\n! style=\"background:#b0c4de;\" width=200px | Role\n! style=\"background:#b0c4de;\" width=200px | Notes\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2002 || ''[[Ice Age (2002 film)|Ice Age]]'' || [[Scrat]], Dodo ||\n|-\n| ''[[Gone Nutty]]'' || Scrat || Short film\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2005 || ''[[Robots (2005 film)|Robots]]'' || Wonderbot, Phone Booth ||\n|-\n| ''[[Aunt Fanny's Tour of Booty]]'' || Hacky || Short film\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | 2006 || ''[[Ice Age: The Meltdown]]'' || rowspan=\"11\" | Scrat || Main role\n|-\n| ''[[No Time for Nuts]]'' || Short film\n|-\n| ''[[Family Guy]]'' || Episode \"[[Sibling Rivalry (Family Guy)|Sibling Rivalry]]\"\n|-\n| 2008 || ''[[Surviving Sid]]'' || Short film\n|-\n| 2009 || ''[[Ice Age: Dawn of the Dinosaurs]]