\n| [[Newport International Film Festival|Jury Award]] || Best Short ||{{nom}}\n|-\n| Oberhausen International Short Film Festival Award || Prize of the Children's Short Film Competition ||{{won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\"|2003 || [[Academy Award]] || Best Animated Feature || rowspan=\"3\"|''[[Ice Age (2002 film)|Ice Age]]'' ||{{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Annie Award]] || Outstanding Directing in an Animated Feature Production<br><small>Shared with [[Carlos Saldanha]] (co-director)</small> ||{{nom}}\n|-\n| [[DVD Exclusive Award]] || Best Audio Commentary, New Release<br><small>Shared with [[Carlos Saldanha]] (co-director)</small> ||{{nom}}\n|-\n| [[National Association of Theatre Owners|ShoWest Convention Award]] || Animation Director of the Year || ||{{won}}\n|-\n| 2013 || Behind the Voice Actors Award || Best Vocal Ensemble in a Feature Film <br><small>Shared with [[Ray Romano]], [[Denis Leary]], [[John Leguizamo]], [[Queen Latifah]], [[Keke Palmer]], [[Seann William Scott]], [[Josh Peck]], [[Wanda Sykes]], [[Jennifer Lopez]], [[Alan Tudyk]], [[Joy Behar]], [[Patrick Stewart]], [[Simon Pegg]] & [[Rebel Wilson]]</small>|| ''[[Ice Age: Continental Drift]]'' ||{{nom}}\n|-\n| 2014 || [[Annie Award]] || Outstanding Achievement in Directing in an Animated Feature Production || ''[[Epic (2013 film)|Epic]]'' ||{{nom}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons}}\n*{{IMDb name|0917188}}\n*[http://movies.ign.com/articles/563/563908p1.html IGN interview]\n*[https://www.bbc.co.uk/films/2004/11/15/chris_wedge_robots_interview.shtml BBC interview]\n\n{{Chris Wedge}}\n{{Blue Sky Studios}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wedge, Chris}}\n[[Category:Animators from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:American animated film directors]]\n[[Category:American animated film producers]]\n[[Category:Animation screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Ohio State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Artists from Binghamton, New York]]\n[[Category:State University of New York at Purchase alumni]]\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Fayetteville-Manlius High School alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Manlius, New York]]\n[[Category:Directors of Best Animated Short Academy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Blue Sky Studios people]]\n[[Category:People from Katonah, New York]]\n[[Category:Film directors from New York (state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American animator}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image         =  Chris Wedge 2014.jpg\n| caption       = Wedge in 2014\n| birth_name    = John Christian Wedge\n| name          = Chris Wedge\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1957|3|20|mf=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[Binghamton, New York]], U.S.\n| nationality   = American\n| education     = [[Fayetteville-Manlius High School]]\n| alma_mater    = [[State University of New York at Purchase]]<br>[[Ohio State University]]\n| occupation    = Film director, film producer, screenwriter, cartoonist, voice actor\n| yearsactive   = 1982\u2013present\n| notable_works = ''[[Ice Age (2002 film)|Ice Age]]''<br>''[[Robots (2005 film)|Robots]]''<br>''[[Epic (2013 film)|Epic]]''<br>''[[Monster Trucks (film)|Monster Trucks]]''\n| spouse        = Jeanne Markel<ref name=TNYTBunnyOscar />\n| children = 2\n}}\n\n'''John Christian Wedge''' (born March 20, 1957) is an American [[animated film]] director,  producer, writer, cartoonist and voice actor, whose films include ''[[Ice Age (2002 film)|Ice Age]]'' (2002), ''[[Robots (2005 film)|Robots]]'' (2005), ''[[Epic (2013 film)|Epic]]'' (2013) and ''[[Monster Trucks (film)|Monster Trucks]]'' (2016). He is a co-founder of the animation studio [[Blue Sky Studios]] and voiced the character [[Scrat]] in the ''[[Ice Age (franchise)|Ice Age]]'' franchise.\n\n==Early life==\nWedge was born in [[Binghamton, New York]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.behindthevoiceactors.com/Chris-Wedge/ |title= Behind The Voice Actors - Chris Wedge |accessdate=April 14, 2014}}</ref> He became interested in animation when he was 12 years old: \"Back then, there was a TV special about kids making cut-out animation in a workshop\u2014as I recall it was Yellow Ball Workshop\u2014it was a clear technique to follow and I followed it. That fascinated me and it got me started. It was so simple, effective and magical in outcome and I stuck with creating things throughout my childhood, teenage years and then college.\"<ref name=PatchKatonah>{{cite news|last=Buchman|first=Lisa|title=Meet Chris Wedge, 'Ice Age' Creator, Katonah Resident|url=http://bedford.patch.com/articles/meet-chris-wedge-ice-age-director-and-katonah-resident|accessdate=November 29, 2012|newspaper=Patch|date=September 12, 2012}}</ref>\n\nHe attended [[Fayetteville-Manlius High School]], graduating in 1975.<ref name=\"distinction\">{{cite web | title = Chris Wedge, Class of 1975, Inducted in 2000 | work = Fayetteville-Manlius Hall of Distinction | publisher = Fayetteville-Manlius Schools | url = http://www.fmschools.org/community.cfm?subpage=16023 | accessdate = May 29, 2011 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110724182939/http://www.fmschools.org/community.cfm?subpage=16023 | archive-date = July 24, 2011 | url-status = dead | df = mdy-all }}</ref> He received his BFA in Film from [[State University of New York at Purchase]] in Purchase, New York in 1981, and subsequently earned his MA in [[computer graphics]] and art education at the [[Ohio State University]]. He has taught animation at the [[School of Visual Arts]] in [[New York City]] where he met his future film directing partner, [[Carlos Saldanha]].\n\n==Career==\nIn 1982, Wedge worked for [[Mathematical Applications Group, Inc.|MAGI]]/SynthaVision, where he was a principal animator on the [[The Walt Disney Company|Disney]] film ''[[Tron]]'', credited as a scene programmer. Some of his other works include ''[[Where the Wild Things Are]]'' (1983), ''George Shrinks'', ''[[The Brave Little Toaster]]'' (1987), and ''Santa Calls''.\n\nWedge is co-founder and Vice President of Creative Development at [[Blue Sky Studios]], one of the premier computer animation studios and producer of Wedge's films. He is the owner of WedgeWorks, a film production company founded by Wedge.\n\nIn the 1990s, he and his studio worked on CGI effects for the movies ''[[Alien Resurrection]]'' and ''[[Titan A.E.]]''\n\nIn 1998, he won an [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]] for the short animated film, ''[[Bunny (1998 film)|Bunny]]''. In 2002, Wedge directed Blue Sky Studios' first computer-animated film ''[[Ice Age (2002 film)|Ice Age]]'' and served as a producer for its sequels. He also voiced [[Scrat]] in the film series, performing the character's \"squeaks and squeals.\"<ref name=\"PS\">{{cite news  | last = LaRue | first = William | title = 'Ice Age' director gives students a look into animation | work = [[The Syracuse Post-Standard]] | publisher = Syracuse.com | date = November 2, 2006 | url = http://www.syracuse.com/living/poststandard/index.ssf?/base/living-2/1162461401265550.xml&coll=1 | accessdate = January 27, 2007 }}{{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> In 2005, Wedge directed ''[[Robots (2005 film)|Robots]]'', based on a story he created with [[William Joyce (writer)|William Joyce]]. In 2013 followed ''[[Epic (2013 film)|Epic]]'', loosely based on Joyce's book, ''The Leaf Men and the Brave Good Bugs''.<ref name=\"Mania\">{{cite news|last=Schneider |first=Karl |title=Chris Wedge to direct THE LEAF MEN AND THE BRAVE GOOD BUGS |work=Movie News, Mania.com |publisher=Mania Entertainment, LLC., citing [[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=August 24, 2006 |url=http://www.mania.com/52071.html |accessdate=January 27, 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927021330/http://www.mania.com/52071.html |archivedate=September 27, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, it was announced that Wedge would direct ''[[Hugo (film)|Hugo]]'' though he was subsequently replaced by [[Martin Scorsese]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Siegel |first=Tatiana |url=https://www.variety.com/article/VR1117985121 |title=Chris Wedge to direct 'Hugo Cabret' |journal=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=2008-05-05 |accessdate=2012-08-24}}</ref> In 2009, it was reported that Wedge would direct an animated feature film adaptation of [[Will Wright (game designer)|Will Wright]]'s ''[[Spore (2008 video game)#Theatrical film|Spore]]'', but since then there has been no further news about the film.<ref>{{cite magazine |first=Marc |last=Graser |url=https://www.variety.com/article/VR1118009454 |title=EA sets up 'Spore' at Fox |magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=October 1, 2009 |accessdate=October 7, 2010}}</ref>\n\nWedge directed the science fiction/action film ''[[Monster Trucks (film)|Monster Trucks]]'' (2016), with a $100 million budget, and starring [[Lucas Till]] and [[Jane Levy]].<ref name=mt>{{cite news|title=Paramount Animation Plans \u2018Monster Trucks\u2019 Live Action-Toon Franchise: In Final Talks With Blue Sky\u2019s Chris Wedge To Direct|url=https://www.deadline.com/2013/07/paramout-animation-plans-monster-trucks-live-action-toon-franchise-in-final-talks-with-chris-wedge-to-direct/|accessdate=August 2, 2013|newspaper=deadline.com|date=July 31, 2013}}</ref> [[Jonathan Aibel and Glenn Berger]] wrote the script for the film,<ref name=\"mt\" /> produced by [[Mary Parent]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Paramount Animation Planning Live Action/Animated Franchise 'Monster Trucks' With Blue Sky's Chris Wedge|url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/paramount-animation-planning-live-action-animated-franchise-monster-trucks-with-blue-skys-chris-wedge-20130801|accessdate=August 2, 2013|newspaper=indiewire.com|date=August 1, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140521032045/http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/paramount-animation-planning-live-action-animated-franchise-monster-trucks-with-blue-skys-chris-wedge-20130801|archive-date=May 21, 2014|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nWedge lives in [[Katonah, New York]]<ref name=PatchKatonah /> with his wife Jeanne Markel.<ref name=TNYTBunnyOscar>{{cite news|last=Staudter|first=Thomas|title='Bunny' From Harrison Competes for Oscar|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/03/21/nyregion/bunny-from-harrison-competes-for-oscar.html|accessdate=June 2, 2013|newspaper=The New York Times|date=March 21, 1999}}</ref> They have a daughter and a son, Sarah and Jack.<ref>{{cite web|title=Chris Wedge Acceptance Speech|url=http://aaspeechesdb.oscars.org/link/071-18/|publisher=The Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences|accessdate=June 2, 2013|quote=And so to my beautiful wife and family, Jean*, Sarah and Jack...}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Director===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:#b0c4de;\"| Year\n! style=\"background:#b0c4de;\" width=200px | Title\n! style=\"background:#b0c4de;\" width=400px | Notes\n|-\n| 1985 || ''Tuber's Two-Step'' || rowspan=\"2\" | Short film\n|-\n| 1987 || ''Balloon Guy''\n|-\n| 1998 || ''[[Bunny (1998 film)|Bunny]]'' || (Short Film) [[Academy Award for Best Animated Short Film]]<br>Also writer\n|-\n| 2002 || ''[[Ice Age (2002 film)|Ice Age]]'' ||  Academy Award nomination for [[Academy Award for Best Animated Feature|Best Animated Feature]]\n|-\n| 2005 || ''[[Robots (2005 film)|Robots]]'' ||\n|-\n| 2013 || ''[[Epic (2013 film)|Epic]]'' || \n|-\n| 2016 || ''[[Monster Trucks (film)|Monster Trucks]]'' ||\n|}\n\n===Producer===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:#b0c4de;\"| Year\n! style=\"background:#b0c4de;\" width=200px | Title\n! style=\"background:#b0c4de;\" width=400px | Notes\n|-\n| 1990 || ''The Mind's Eye'' || Short film\n|-\n| 2002 || ''[[Gone Nutty]]'' || rowspan=\"4\" | Executive producer\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2006 || ''[[Ice Age: The Meltdown]]''\n|-\n| ''[[No Time for Nuts]]''\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2008 || ''[[Horton Hears a Who! (film)|Horton Hears a Who!]]'' \n|-\n| ''[[Surviving Sid]]'' || Short film<br />Executive producer\n|-\n| 2009 || ''[[Ice Age: Dawn of the Dinosaurs]]'' || rowspan=\"7\"  | Executive producer\n|-\n| 2011 || ''[[Rio (2011 film)|Rio]]'' \n|-\n| 2012 || ''[[Ice Age: Continental Drift]]''\n|-\n| 2014 || ''[[Rio 2]]''\n|-\n| 2016 || ''[[Ice Age: Collision Course]]''<ref name=USATSquirrelMacy>{{cite news|last1=Truitt|first1=Brian|title=Exclusive: 'Ice Age' squirrel to make Macy's debut|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/movies/2015/10/22/exclusive-ice-age-scrat-balloon-macys-thanksgiving-day-parade/74366580/|accessdate=October 29, 2015|work=USA Today|date=October 22, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2017 || ''[[Ferdinand (film)|Ferdinand]]''\n|-\n| 2019 || ''[[Spies in Disguise]]''\n|}\n\n===Animator===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:#b0c4de;\"| Year\n! style=\"background:#b0c4de;\" width=200px | Title\n! style=\"background:#b0c4de;\" width=400px | Notes\n|-\n| 1982 || ''[[Tron]]'' || Principal animator\n|-\n| 1987 || ''Balloon Guy'' || Animator\n|-\n| 1996 || ''[[Joe's Apartment]]'' || Animation director\n|}\n\n===Writer===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:#b0c4de;\"| Year\n! style=\"background:#b0c4de;\" width=200px | Title\n! style=\"background:#b0c4de;\" width=400px | Notes\n|-\n| 1998 || ''[[Bunny (1998 film)|Bunny]]'' ||\n|-\n| 2013 || ''[[Epic (2013 film)|Epic]]'' || Story\n|}\n\n===Actor===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 95%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:#b0c4de;\"| Year\n! style=\"background:#b0c4de;\" width=200px | Title\n! style=\"background:#b0c4de;\" width=200px | Role\n! style=\"background:#b0c4de;\" width=200px | Notes\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2002 || ''[[Ice Age (2002 film)|Ice Age]]'' || [[Scrat]], Dodo ||\n|-\n| ''[[Gone Nutty]]'' || Scrat || Short film\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2005 || ''[[Robots (2005 film)|Robots]]'' || Wonderbot, Phone Booth ||\n|-\n| ''[[Aunt Fanny's Tour of Booty]]'' || Hacky || Short film\n|-\n| rows