lan|website=Elite Daily|language=en|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref>\n\nAs per the latest reports, Season 2 will be converted into television series starring [[Saturday Night Live]] cast member [[Kate McKinnon]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.koco.com/article/report-podcast-about-joe-exotic-to-be-turned-into-television-series/29718016|title=Report: Podcast about 'Joe Exotic' to be turned into television series|last=Staff|first=KOCO|date=2019-11-07|website=KOCO|language=en|access-date=2020-04-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tampabay.com/arts-entertainment/2020/03/27/more-tiger-king-kate-mckinnon-to-play-carole-baskin-in-new-tv-series/|title=More Tiger King: Kate McKinnon to play Carole Baskin in new TV series|website=Tampa Bay Times|language=en|access-date=2020-04-25}}</ref> She will be reprising the role of [[Carole Baskin]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.refinery29.com/en-us/2020/04/9640222/tiger-king-sequel-season-2|title=We Might Be Getting A Bonus Episode Of \"Tiger King\"|last=Reilly|first=Kaitlin|website=www.refinery29.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2020/03/tiger-king-kate-mckinnon-carole-baskin-casting|title=Yes, Kate McKinnon Is Set to Play Tiger King\u2019s Carole Baskin|last=Desta|first=Yohana|website=Vanity Fair|language=en|access-date=2020-04-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/3am/celebrity-news/tiger-kings-carole-baskin-played-21820662|title=Tiger King's Carole Baskin to be played by Kate McKinnon in new serialisation|last=Sulway|first=Verity|date=2020-04-06|website=mirror|access-date=2020-04-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2020/03/kate-mckinnon-stars-as-carole-baskin-in-tiger-king-series.html|title=Hey, All You Cool Cats and Kittens, Kate McKinnon Is Playing Carole Baskin|last=Murphy|first=Chris|date=2020-03-27|website=Vulture|language=en-us|access-date=2020-04-25}}</ref> The latter has requested the show use only [[computer-generated imagery]] of tigers instead of real ones.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/04/01/tiger-kings-carole-baskin-urges-kate-mckinnon-not-use-live-tigers-new-miniseries-big-cats-12490204/|title=Tiger King's Carole Baskin urges Kate McKinnon not to use live animals in series|date=2020-04-01|website=Metro|language=en|access-date=2020-04-25}}</ref>\n\n== See Also ==\n* [[Dr._Death_(podcast)|Dr. Death]]\n\t\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n<!--- Categories --->\n[[Category:Investigative journalism]]\n[[Category:Infotainment]]\n[[Category:Audio podcasts]]\n[[Category:2019 podcast debuts]]\n[[Category: Crime podcasts]]\n", "name_user": "LiamH987", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Over_my_dead_body_(podcast)"}
{"title_page": "Dandiya Raas", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=April 2019}}\n{{Other uses}}\n{{Refimprove|date=March 2009}}\n[[File:Children performing Dandiya in Palace Grounds, Bangalore.jpg|thumb|Dandiya Raas dance by children during Navratri in Bangalore]]\n'''Raas''' or '''Dandiya Raas''' is the socio-religious [[folk dance]] originating from Indian state of [[Gujarat]] and popularly performed in the festival of [[Navaratri]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=WDk9AQAAIAAJ&q=Raas+dandiya&dq=Raas+dandiya&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjZ0qWCvfbkAhVHXSsKHaB6A1UQ6AEIYTAJ|title=ISME Yearbook|last=Education|first=International Society for Music|date=1984|publisher=B. Schott's S\u00f6hne|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=118|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /> The dance is performed in the [[Marwar]] region of the [[Rajasthan]] too.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=L7RMAQAAIAAJ&q=rajasthan+dandiya+raas&dq=rajasthan+dandiya+raas&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi5k-LywfbkAhXbfysKHWCEAmkQ6AEIYDAI|title=Khy\u0101ta: itih\u0101sa, kal\u0101, eva\u1e43 sa\u1e43skr\u0325ti k\u012b \u015bodha patrik\u0101|last=|first=|date=2002|publisher=Marubh\u016bmi \u015aodha Sa\u1e43sth\u0101na|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=240|language=hi}}</ref> \n\n==Etymology==\n[[File:Dandiya.jpg|thumb|Dandiya]]\nThe word \"Raas\" comes from the [[Sanskrit language|Sanskrit]] word \"[[Rasa (aesthetics)|Rasa]]\", an aesthetic Indian concept related to emotions and feelings. [[Kapila Vatsyayan]] argued that aesthetic theory of the Rasa gives the underlying unity to the Indian arts.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=I2K1AAAAIAAJ&q=traditions+of+indian+folk+dance+kapila+vatsyayan+pdf&dq=traditions+of+indian+folk+dance+kapila+vatsyayan+pdf&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjvw9u7y_bkAhVXbn0KHXQFAUMQ6AEIKjAA|title=Traditions of Indian folk dance|last=Vatsyayan|first=Kapila|date=1987|publisher=Clarion Books associated with Hind Pocket Books|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=5|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Forms of Raas==\nDandiya Raas, Gopgunthan Solanga Raas and Mer Dandiya Raas are the popular forms of Raas. In [[Saurashtra (region)|Saurashtra]], Raas is performed by the men and the dance performed by women is called as Raasda. Element of dance is more prominent in the Raas while music is more prominent in Raasda.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=nuWBch2jTqAC&pg=PA59&dq=Raas+dandiya&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjOgpjbu_bkAhU86XMBHeTRCXMQ6AEINjAC#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Musical Heritage of India|last=Sharma|first=Manorma|date=2007|publisher=APH Publishing|year=|isbn=9788131300466|location=|pages=59|language=en}}</ref>[[File:Mer Dandiya.jpg|thumb|Mers of Saurashtra performing Dandiya Raas]]\n\n== Format ==\nBoth men and women traditionally play ''dandiya-raas'' and the dance operates in pairs, meaning the group must contain an even number. Generally two lines are formed, with partners facing each other:<blockquote>The lines move clockwise, and each person steps forward to hit sticks with their partner, then moves on two people. At the end of the line, each turns and joins the line opposite, so the movement is continuous. The music starts very slowly [\u2026] It is an eight-beat time cycle called Kaherva and performed in the following manner: on the first beat your own sticks are hit together, followed by right sticks with your partner, then left sticks (or the same stick if using one). Each one then turns away to the left to hit their own sticks together before turning back to the partner to hit right sticks again, and before moving on two places to a new partner.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Performing faith|last=David|first=|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=138-9}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n\n{{Dance in India}}\n\n[[Category:Culture of Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Folk dances of Gujarat]]\n[[Category:Folk dances of Rajasthan]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=April 2019}}\n{{Other uses}}\n{{Refimprove|date=March 2009}}\n[[File:Children performing Dandiya in Palace Grounds, Bangalore.jpg|thumb|Dandiya Raas dance by children during Navratri in Bangalore]]\n'''Raas''' or '''Dandiya Raas''' is the socio-religious [[folk dance]] originating from Indian state of [[Gujarat]] and popularly performed in the festival of [[Navaratri]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=WDk9AQAAIAAJ&q=Raas+dandiya&dq=Raas+dandiya&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjZ0qWCvfbkAhVHXSsKHaB6A1UQ6AEIYTAJ|title=ISME Yearbook|last=Education|first=International Society for Music|date=1984|publisher=B. Schott's S\u00f6hne|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=118|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /> The dance is performed in the [[Marwar]] region of the [[Rajasthan]] too.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=L7RMAQAAIAAJ&q=rajasthan+dandiya+raas&dq=rajasthan+dandiya+raas&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi5k-LywfbkAhXbfysKHWCEAmkQ6AEIYDAI|title=Khy\u0101ta: itih\u0101sa, kal\u0101, eva\u1e43 sa\u1e43skr\u0325ti k\u012b \u015bodha patrik\u0101|last=|first=|date=2002|publisher=Marubh\u016bmi \u015aodha Sa\u1e43sth\u0101na|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=240|language=hi}}</ref> \n\n==Etymology==\n[[File:Dandiya.jpg|thumb|Dandiya]]\nThe word \"Raas\" comes from the [[Sanskrit language|Sanskrit]] word \"[[Rasa (aesthetics)|Rasa]]\", an aesthetic Indian concept related to emotions and feelings. [[Kapila Vatsyayan]] argued that aesthetic theory of the Rasa gives the underlying unity to the Indian arts.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=I2K1AAAAIAAJ&q=traditions+of+indian+folk+dance+kapila+vatsyayan+pdf&dq=traditions+of+indian+folk+dance+kapila+vatsyayan+pdf&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjvw9u7y_bkAhVXbn0KHXQFAUMQ6AEIKjAA|title=Traditions of Indian folk dance|last=Vatsyayan|first=Kapila|date=1987|publisher=Clarion Books associated with Hind Pocket Books|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=5|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Forms of Raas==\nDandiya Raas, Gopgunthan Solanga Raas and Mer Dandiya Raas are the popular forms of Raas. In [[Saurashtra (region)|Saurashtra]], Raas is performed by the men and the dance performed by women is called as Raasda. Element of dance is more prominent in the Raas while music is more prominent in Raasda.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=nuWBch2jTqAC&pg=PA59&dq=Raas+dandiya&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjOgpjbu_bkAhU86XMBHeTRCXMQ6AEINjAC#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Musical Heritage of India|last=Sharma|first=Manorma|date=2007|publisher=APH Publishing|year=|isbn=9788131300466|location=|pages=59|language=en}}</ref>[[File:Mer Dandiya.jpg|thumb|Mers of Saurashtra performing Dandiya Raas]]\n<br />\n\n== Format ==\nBoth men and women traditionally play ''dandiya-raas'' and the dance operates in pairs, meaning the group must contain an even number. Generally two lines are formed, with partners facing each other:<blockquote>The lines move clockwise, and each person steps forward to hit sticks with their partner, then moves on two people. At the end of the line, each turns and joins the line opposite, so the movement is continuous. The music starts very slowly [\u2026] It is an eight-beat time cycle called Kaherva and performed in the following manner: on the first beat your own sticks are hit together, followed by right sticks with your partner, then left sticks (or the same stick if using one). Each one then turns away to the left to hit their own sticks together before turning back to the partner to hit right sticks again, and before moving on two places to a new partner.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Performing faith|last=David|first=|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=138-9}}</ref></blockquote>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Dance in India}}\n==External Links==\n{{Commons category}}\n[[Category:Culture of Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Folk dances of Gujarat]]\n[[Category:Folk dances of Rajasthan]]\n", "name_user": "Jessicapierce", "label": "safe", "comment": "minor copy edits", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dandiya_Raas"}
{"title_page": "Ebrahim Hatamikia", "text_new": "{{short description|Iranian screenwriter and film director|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Ebrahim Hatamikia\n| image         = Exodus movie press conference 2020-02-07 37.jpg\n| imagesize     =\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1961|9|23|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[Tehran]], [[Iran]]\n| death_date    =\n| death_place   =\n| death_cause   =\n| nationality   = [[Iranian peoples|Iranian]]\n| education     = [[Screenwriting#Screenwriting education|Screenwriting]]\n| alma_mater    = [[Tehran University of Art]]\n| occupation    = [[Film director]], [[Screenwriter]], [[Cinematographer]] and [[Actor]]\n| years_active  = 1979\u2013present\n| spouse        =\n| children      = Nayereh Hatamikia<br>Yousef Hatamikia<br>Esmaeil Hatamikia\n| awards        = [[Crystal Simorgh]]\n| website       =\n| module        = {{Infobox military person\n | embed         = yes\n | allegiance    = [[Armed Forces of the Islamic Republic of Iran|Iran]]\n | branch        = [[Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps|Revolutionary Guards]]\n | serviceyears  = 1981\u2013early 1990s\n | unit          = Audiovisual unit\n | battles       = [[Iran\u2013Iraq War]]\n }}\n| signature     =\n}}\n\n'''Ebrahim Hatamikia''' (born 23 September 1961) is an [[Iran]]ian  [[Film director]], [[Screenwriter]], [[Cinematographer]] and [[Actor]].\n\n== Biography ==\nEbrahim Hatamikia, who is internationally renowned for his role in the [[cinema of Iran]] in the 1990s, was born in 1961 in [[Tehran]] to a Persian father and Azeri mother.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://hamshahrionline.ir/details/65569|title=\u0632\u0646\u062f\u06af\u06cc\u0646\u0627\u0645\u0647: \u0627\u0628\u0631\u0627\u0647\u06cc\u0645 \u062d\u0627\u062a\u0645\u06cc \u06a9\u06cc\u0627|website=hamshahrionline.ir|access-date=2018-05-19}}</ref> He left the Art University where he studied script writing. He began his directing career with the film ''The Identity'' in 1987 and some short films and documentaries about the [[Iran\u2013Iraq War]]. His movies are considered to be the best that tackle the war and the issues surrounding it. His works have often received admiration in national film festivals. ''[[The Glass Agency]]'' and ''In the Name of the Father'' have won him the best screenplay and directing awards in the sixteenth and twenty-fourth [[Fajr International Film Festival]] respectively. His recent works have also been on international screens: ''The Glass Agency'' in Berlin and ''The Red Ribbon'' in San Sebasti\u00e1n.\n\n== Filmography ==\n[[File:Hatamikia receives Ghoghnos best director award.jpg|thumb|Hatamikia receives Ghoghnos best director award]]\n=== Feature films ===\n* ''[[The Identity (film)|The Identity]]'' (1987)\n* ''[[The Scout (1989 film)|The Scout]]'' (1989)\n* ''[[The Immigrant (1990 film)|The Immigrant]]'' (1990)\n* ''[[Union of the Righteous]]'' (1991)\n* ''[[From Karkheh to Rhein]]'' (1993)\n* ''[[The Green Ashes]]'' (1994)\n* ''[[The Scent of Joseph's Shirt]]'' (1996)\n* ''[[The Minoo Tower]]'' (1996)\n* ''[[The Glass Agency]]'' (1998)\n* ''[[The Red Ribbon]]'' (1999)\n* ''[[The Dead Wave]]'' (2001)\n* ''[[Low Heights]]'' (2002)\n* ''[[In Amethyst Color]]'' (2004)\n* ''[[In the Name of the Father (2006 film)|In the Name of the Father]]'' (2006)\n* ''[[Invitation (2008 film)|Invitation]]'' (2008)\n* ''[[The Report of a Party]]'' (2011)\n* ''[[Che (2014 film)|Che]]'' (2014)\n* ''[[Bodyguard (2016 film)|Bodyguard]]'' (2016)\n* ''[[Damascus Time]]'' (2018)\n* ''[[Exodus (2020 film)|Exodus]]'' (2020)\n\n=== Short films ===\n* ''Blinds of Heart'' (1982)\n* ''Proud's Sequel'' (1982)\n* ''The Promised'' (1982)\n* ''[[Sacred Soil]]'' (1984)\n* ''[[The Path (1985 film)|The Path]]'' (1985)\n* ''[[Red Ruff]]'' (1985)\n\n=== TV series ===\n* ''[[Ochre (TV series)|Ochre]]'' (2000\u20132001)\n* ''[[Green Ring (TV series)|Green Ring]]'' (2005\u20132006)\n\n== Awards and nominations ==\n{{Expand list|date=March 2020}}\n\n{| class=\"wikita